<header>
<div class="blogparent">“<a href="/m" rel="tag">Marketing Your Music</a>”:</div>
<h1>Small gifts go a long way</h1>
<p class="postdate">2000-05-30</p>
</header>

<p>
	Years ago, I worked at Warner/Chappell Music Publishing.
	Since it’s the largest music publisher in the world, I dealt with thousands of songwriters.
	Most of them, I can’t remember their names.
</p><p>
	Three times, and only three times, I got a surprise gift from a songwriter.
</p><p>
	James Mastro, a great songwriter from Hoboken, got me a cool little “Mother Mary” keychain when he was touring in Spain.
</p><p>
	Gerry DeVeaux, a successful R&amp;B / dance songwriter, got me some funky plastic fish with lights inside, like Christmas ornaments, when he went to the Bahamas.
</p><p>
	And Jane Kelly Williams got me a red sweatshirt from the Gap, for helping her out with a demo session.
</p><p>
	Can you believe I remember these details 20 years later?
	Believe it!
</p><p>
	A little gift you might give to someone, as you climb the ladder of success, may go a long long way, and mean a lot to someone down the road.
</p><p>
	If any of the three people above called me today to ask a favor, you can be sure I’d stop what I was doing to help them out.
</p><p>
	Be generous.
	It will be returned.
	You’re going to see the same faces for years to come.
</p>
<img src="/images/small-gifts.gif">

